{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"45cb8fc6-00d5-4e5e-bd0c-83cb2f7f4fda","content":"This project uses **xUnit v3** with **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (MTP) enabled. Use the `--filter` flag with a `FullyQualifiedName` contains match:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nThis filters to only tests whose fully qualified name contains `Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests`, excluding `InventoryServiceTests`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"358f2c97-4b84-40ee-9f26-6ab684402387","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is xUnit v3 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) enabled (`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`). The filter syntax for MTP with xUnit v3 uses `--filter` but with a different syntax than VSTest.\n\nFor xUnit v3 on MTP, the filter syntax uses treenode-filter. To filter by class, I would use:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"Type=ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. With MTP + xUnit v3, the filter syntax is different. xUnit v3 uses its own filter syntax.\n\n\nActually, with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, `dotnet test` acts as a wrapper for MTP, and the filter syntax depends on the framework adapter. For xUnit v3, the filter property for the class name is either `Type` or `FullyQualifiedName`, so I'd use something like `dotnet test --filter \"Type=ShoppingCartTests\"` with the MTP filter format.\n\nWait, let me reconsider how this actually works. When MTP is enabled, `dotnet test --filter` translates to `--treenode-filter` for the underlying test runner, which uses a hierarchical path-like syntax for xUnit v3. So the simplest approach would be using the property-based syntax with `FullyQualifiedName` to match the class name. I'm working through the filter syntax for running the ShoppingCartTests class specifically. The fully qualified name would be `Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests`, and I can use the `~` contains operator with `dotnet test --filter` to match it, which should work whether we're in standard VSTest mode or the MTP bridge mode.","outputTokens":1041,"requestId":"082E:E43FA:D1CFAE:F1F631:69EAC4A7"},"id":"282c58f3-c055-4ec9-838d-2823238322fe","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:17:49.185Z","parentId":"9e821ac6-d235-490a-b959-39a23c2e74fe"}
